      "note22": {
        "marker": "22.",
        "context": null,
        "pid": "141535640",
        "id": "note22",
        "text": "<p data-aid=\"141536836\" id=\"note22_p1\">We remember the words of James that inspired Joseph Smith to &#x201C;ask of God&#x201D; (<a class=\"scripture-ref\" href=\"/study/scriptures/nt/james/1.5?lang=eng#p5\">James 1:5<\/a>). Less familiar are the preceding verses: <\/p>\n<p data-aid=\"141536839\" id=\"note22_p2\">&#x201C;My brethren, count it all joy when ye fall into many afflictions; <\/p>\n<p data-aid=\"141536842\" id=\"note22_p3\">&#x201C;Knowing this, that the trying of your faith worketh patience.<\/p>\n<p data-aid=\"141536846\" id=\"note22_p4\">&#x201C;But let patience have her perfect work, that ye may be perfect and entire, wanting nothing&#x201D; (Joseph Smith Translation, James 1:2 [in <a class=\"scripture-ref\" href=\"/study/scriptures/nt/james/1.2?lang=eng#p2\">James 1:2, footnote <i>a<\/i><\/a>]; <a class=\"scripture-ref\" href=\"/study/scriptures/nt/james/1.3-4?lang=eng#p3\">James 1:3&#x2013;4<\/a>).<\/p>",
